B1(a) — What type of ML problem is this?
This is a regression problem because we are predicting items_sold, which is a number.
The input features include things like promotion type, store location, store size, footfall, etc. Using these, the model predicts how many items will be sold.
We can then compare the predicted values for different promotions and choose the one that gives the highest sales.

B1(b) — Why items_sold is better than revenue?
Revenue depends on price and discounts, so it can sometimes give a wrong idea.
For example, a flat discount may sell more items but at a lower price, while another promotion may sell fewer items but at a higher price and give more revenue.
So if we use revenue, the model might prefer high-price options instead of high sales.
items_sold is better because it directly shows how many items were sold, which makes it a fair comparison between promotions.

B1(c) — Why one global model is a bad idea?
Using one model for all stores is not a good idea because all stores are different.
For example, urban stores may have more customers and different preferences compared to rural stores. Some promotions may work well in one type of store but not in another.
If we use one model, it mixes all this data together and learns an average pattern, which may not work well for any specific store.
A better approach is to first group similar stores (based on location, footfall, etc.) and then train separate models for each group.
This way, each model learns from similar data and gives better predictions.
